# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: freeman-brown
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:freeman-brown/1882-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1882 throughout the world.
[src:freeman-brown/1882-worcester-worcesters-season] The **1882 Worcester Worcesters** finished with an 18–66 record, last place in the National League.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] Find a Grave was created in 1995 by Jim Tipton of Salt Lake City, Utah, to support his hobby of visiting the burial sites of famous celebrities.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] Tipton described his early childhood as a nerdy kid with a fascination for graves, and an interest in HTML.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] Find a Grave was launched as a commercial entity in 1998, first as a trade name and then incorporated in 2000.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] In 2010, Find a Grave was expanded to include graves of non-celebrities in order to allow online visitors to pay respect to their deceased relatives or friends.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] The website contains listings of cemeteries and graves from around the world.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] American cemeteries are organized by state and county, and many cemetery records contain Google Maps (with GPS coordinates supplied by contributors) and photographs of the cemeteries and gravesites.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] Individual grave records may contain dates and places of birth and death, biographical information, cemetery and plot information, photographs (of the grave marker, the individual, etc.), and contributor information.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] Interment listings are added by individuals, genealogical societies, cemetery associations, and other institutions such as the International Wargraves Photography Project.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] The website is often recommended as a resource for genealogy research.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] Find a Grave also maintains lists of memorials of famous persons by their "claim to fame", such as Medal of Honor recipients, religious figures, and educators.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] Find a Grave exercises editorial control over these listings.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] Starting from May 18, 2023, memorials became able to be marked with a "Veteran" tag.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] Website policy is to remove memorials or transfer their management at the request of an immediate family member.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] In January 2022, following complaints, Find a Grave announced a new policy for memorials of recently deceased persons.
[src:freeman-brown/find-a-grave] Under the new policy, any photos or personal information, including obituaries, are hidden for three months.
[src:freeman-brown/freeman-brown] Outside of baseball, he worked for the newspapers the *Worcester Spy* and *Worcester Telegram*, as well as serving as clerk of the overseers of the poor for 25 years.
[src:freeman-brown/freeman-brown] He died in Worcester, Massachusetts on December 27, 1916.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Hubbardston, the "Northeast Quarter" of Rutland, was incorporated as a separate district in 1767 and named for Thomas Hubbard (1702–1773), Commissary General of the Province of Massachusetts and Treasurer of Harvard College.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] It is reported in local history that in view of the honor of giving his name to the town, Hubbard promised to provide the glass for the windows of the first meeting house built in town.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] To make his liberality more conspicuous, the people planned for extra windows, but when Hubbard died in 1773, his estate was so complicated that the town of Hubbardston received nothing and was obliged to glaze the windows at its own expense.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] In 1737 Eleazer Brown located on a farm of 60 acres given him by the proprietors of Rutland on the condition that he operate a public house or inn.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Until 1746, Brown and his wife were the only inhabitants of Hubbardston.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] After Eleazer's death (reportedly killed by a deer), Mrs.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Brown was then the only occupant of town for several years, and she kept the public house for prominent travelers.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] In 1749, Israel Green moved into Hubbardston.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] His daughter, Molly Green, is reported to be the first child born in Hubbardston.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Green was the first chairman of the board of selectmen.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] The town's early economy was based on agriculture and small-scale chair, boot, and shoe manufacturing.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] It is described by historians as a poor town, sparsely settled and almost wholly agricultural, but having sawmills, potash works, and cottage industries such as the making of palm-leaf hats.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] By the 19th century, dairy and berry farming and market gardening were major pursuits in the town.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Immigrants from Ireland, French Canada, England, Sweden, and Finland moved to town to work on local farms.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Hubbardston was represented by 65 men during the Revolutionary War.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Captain Adam Wheeler, one of the leaders of Shays' Rebellion, an armed uprising in central and western Massachusetts, was from Hubbardston.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] In 1786, eighty men from the town marched to Worcester under Wheeler's command and, joining hundreds of other farmers, took control of the courthouse to protest the widespread foreclosures and seizures of property by creditors that occurred during the cash-poor 18th century.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Hubbardston furnished 164 men during the Civil War.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Forty-four were killed or died of illness.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Hubbardston is home to the invention of the first backhoe swing frame, developed in July 1947 by Vaino J.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Holopainen (pronounced "Waino") and Roy E.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Handy, Jr., (thus the company name "Wain-Roy") and assigned to Wain-Roy Corporation of Hubbardston.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] According to the United States Census Bureau, the town has a total area of 42.0 square miles (109 km2), of which 41.0 square miles (106 km2) is land and 0.9 square miles (2.3 km2), or 2.19%, is water.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Hubbardston is bounded on the northwest by Phillipston and Templeton, on the northeast by Gardner and Westminster, on the southeast by Princeton and Rutland, and on the southwest by Barre.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] As of the census of 2000, there were 3,909 people, 1,308 households, and 1,071 families residing in the town.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] The population density was 95.3 inhabitants per square mile (36.8/km2).
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] There were 1,360 housing units at an average density of 33.1 per square mile (12.8/km2).
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] The racial makeup of the town was 98.39% White, 0.15% African American, 0.08% Native American, 0.49% Asian, 0.28% from other races, and 0.61% from two or more races.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 1.33% of the population.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] There were 1,308 households, out of which 43.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 73.2% were married couples living together, 5.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 18.1% were non-families.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] 13.7% of all households were made up of individuals, and 4.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] The average household size was 2.97 and the average family size was 3.28.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] In the town, the population was spread out, with 31.1% under the age of 18, 4.8% from 18 to 24, 34.6% from 25 to 44, 22.6% from 45 to 64, and 6.9% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] For every 100 females, there were 102.3 males.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 100.9 males.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] The median income for a household in the town was $61,462, and the median income for a family was $66,058.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Males had a median income of $48,730 versus $33,654 for females.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] The per capita income for the town was $23,072.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] About 2.1% of families and 3.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 3.4% of those under the age of 18 and 7.9% of those 65 and older.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Hubbardson is part of the Quabbin Regional School District along with Barre, Hardwick, New Braintree, and Oakham.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Elementary school students attend Hubbardston Center School, from grades K to 5, while middle school students attend Quabbin Regional Middle School from grades 6 to 8, and high school students attend Quabbin Regional High School from grades 9 to 12.
[src:freeman-brown/hubbardston-massachusetts] Starting the 2020–2021 School year, grade 6 was moved up to the Quabbin Regional Middle School.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Formed in 1876 and 1901, respectively, the NL and AL cemented their cooperation with the National Agreement in 1903, making MLB the oldest major professional sports league in the United States and Canada.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] They remained legally separate entities until 2000, when they merged into a single organization led by the commissioner of baseball.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball's first all-professional team, the Cincinnati Red Stockings, was founded in 1869.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The first few decades of professional baseball saw rivalries between leagues, and players often jumped from one team or league to another.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] These practices were essentially ended by the National Agreement of 1903, in which AL and NL agreed to respect each other's player contracts, including the contentious reserve clause, which bound players to their teams.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The period from about 1900 to 1920 was the dead-ball era, when home runs were rarely hit.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Professional baseball was rocked by the Black Sox Scandal, a conspiracy to fix the 1919 World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball survived the scandal, albeit with major changes in its governance, as the relatively weak National Commission was replaced with a powerful commissioner of baseball with near-unlimited authority over the sport.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB rose in popularity in the decade following the Black Sox Scandal, and unlike major leagues in other sports, it endured the Great Depression and World War II without any of its teams folding.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Shortly after the war, Jackie Robinson broke baseball's color barrier.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Some teams moved to different cities in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The AL and NL added eight clubs in the 1960s, which started the expansion era: two in 1961, two in 1962, and four in 1969.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Player discontent with established labor practices, especially the reserve clause, led to the organization of the Major League Baseball Players Association to collectively bargain with the owners, which in turn led to the introduction of free agency in baseball.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Modern stadiums with artificial turf surfaces began to change the game in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Home runs began to dominate the game during the 1990s.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In the mid-2000s, media reports disclosed the use of anabolic steroids among MLB players; a 2006–07 investigation produced the *Mitchell Report*, which found that many players had used steroids and other performance-enhancing substances, including at least one player from each team.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB is the third-wealthiest professional sports league in the world by revenue after the National Football League (NFL) and the National Basketball Association (NBA).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball games are broadcast on television, radio, and the internet throughout North America and in several other countries.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB has the highest total season attendance of any sports league in the world; in 2025, it drew 71.4 million spectators.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB also oversees Minor League Baseball, which comprises lower-tier teams affiliated with the major league clubs, the MLB Draft League, a hybrid amateur-professional showcase league, and the Arizona Fall League, an off-season showcase league for minor league players.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB and the World Baseball Softball Confederation jointly manage the international World Baseball Classic tournament.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The New York Yankees have the most championships with 27.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The reigning champions are the Los Angeles Dodgers, who defeated the Toronto Blue Jays in the 2025 World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In the 1860s, aided by soldiers playing the game in camp during the Civil War, "New York"-style baseball expanded into a national game and spawned baseball's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The NABBP existed as an amateur league for 12 years.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] By 1867, more than 400 clubs were members.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Most of the strongest clubs remained those based in the northeastern United States.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] For professional baseball's founding year, MLB uses the year 1869—when the first professional team, the Cincinnati Red Stockings, was established.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] A schism developed between professional and amateur ballplayers after the founding of the Cincinnati club.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The NABBP split into an amateur organization and a professional organization.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The National Association of Professional Base Ball Players, often known as the National Association (NA), was formed in 1871.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Its amateur counterpart disappeared after only a few years.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The modern Chicago Cubs and Atlanta Braves franchises trace their histories back to the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players in the 1870s.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1876, the National League of Professional Base Ball Clubs (later known as the National League or NL) was established after the NA proved ineffective.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The league placed its emphasis on clubs rather than on players.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Clubs could now enforce player contracts, preventing players from jumping to higher-paying clubs.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Clubs were required to play the full schedule of games instead of forfeiting scheduled games when the club was no longer in the running for the league championship, which happened frequently under the NA.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] A concerted effort was made to curb gambling on games, which was leaving the validity of results in doubt.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The first game in the NL—on Saturday, April 22, 1876 (at Jefferson Street Grounds in Philadelphia)—is often pointed to as the beginning of MLB.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The early years of the NL were tumultuous, with threats from rival leagues and a rebellion by players against the hated "reserve clause", which restricted the free movement of players between clubs.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Teams came and went; 1882 was the first season where the league's membership was the same as the preceding season's, and only four franchises survived to see 1900.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Competitor leagues formed regularly and also disbanded regularly.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The most successful was the American Association (1882–1891), sometimes called the "beer and whiskey league" for its tolerance of the sale of alcoholic beverages to spectators.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] For several years, the NL and American Association champions met in a postseason championship series—the first attempt at a World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The two leagues merged in 1892 as a single 12-team NL, but the NL dropped four teams after the 1899 season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] This led to the formation of the American League (AL) in 1901 under president Ban Johnson, and the resulting bidding war for players led to widespread contract-breaking and legal disputes.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The war between the AL and NL sent shockwaves throughout the baseball world.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] At a meeting at the Leland Hotel in Chicago in 1901, the other baseball leagues negotiated a plan to maintain their independence.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] A new National Association was formed to oversee these minor leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] After 1902, the NL, AL, and NA signed a new National Agreement, which tied independent contracts to the reserve-clause contracts.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The agreement also set up a formal classification system for minor leagues, the forerunner of today's system that was refined by Branch Rickey.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Several other early defunct baseball leagues are considered major leagues, and their statistics and records are included with those of the two modern major leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1969, the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball officially recognized six major leagues: the National League, American League, American Association, Union Association (1884), Players' League (1890), and Federal League (1914–1915).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The status of the National Association as a major league has been a point of dispute among baseball researchers; while its statistics are not recognized by Major League Baseball, its statistics *are* included with those of other major leagues by some baseball reference websites, such as Retrosheet.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Some researchers, including Nate Silver, dispute the major-league status of the Union Association by pointing out that franchises came and went and that the St.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis club was deliberately "stacked"; the St.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis club was owned by the league's president and it was the only club that was close to major-league caliber.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2021, baseball reference website Baseball-Reference.com began to include statistics from those seven leagues into their major-league statistics.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The period between 1900 and 1919 is commonly referred to as the "dead-ball era".
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Games of this era tended to be low-scoring and were often dominated by pitchers, such as Walter Johnson, Cy Young, Christy Mathewson, Mordecai Brown, and Grover Cleveland Alexander.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The term also accurately describes the condition of the baseball itself.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The baseball used American rather than the modern Australian wool yarn and was not wound as tightly, affecting the distance that it would travel.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] More significantly, balls were kept in play until they were mangled, soft and sometimes lopsided.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] During this era, a baseball cost $3, (equivalent to $56 in 2025), and owners were reluctant to purchase new balls.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Fans were expected to throw back fouls and (rare) home runs.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseballs also became stained with tobacco juice, grass, and mud, and sometimes the juice of licorice, which some players would chew for the purpose of discoloring the ball.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Also, pitchers could manipulate the ball through the use of the spitball (In 1921, use of this pitch was restricted to a few pitchers with a grandfather clause).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Hitting methods like the Baltimore chop were used to increase the number of infield singles.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] On a successful Baltimore chop, the batter hits the ball forcefully into the ground, causing it to bounce so high that the batter reaches first base before the ball can be fielded and thrown to the first baseman.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The adoption of the foul strike rule—in the NL in 1901, in the AL two years later—quickly sent baseball from a high-scoring game to one where scoring runs became a struggle.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Before this rule, foul balls were not counted as strikes: a batter could foul off any number of pitches with no strikes counted against him; this gave an enormous advantage to the batter.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] After the 1919 World Series between the Chicago White Sox and Cincinnati Reds, baseball was rocked by allegations of a game-fixing scheme known as the Black Sox Scandal.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Eight players—"Shoeless" Joe Jackson, Eddie Cicotte, Claude "Lefty" Williams, George "Buck" Weaver, Arnold "Chick" Gandil, Fred McMullin, Charles "Swede" Risberg, and Oscar "Happy" Felsch—intentionally lost the World Series in exchange for a ring worth $100,000 (equivalent to $1,860,000 in 2025).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Despite being acquitted, all were permanently banned from MLB.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball's popularity increased in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1920 season was notable for the death of Ray Chapman of the Cleveland Indians.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Chapman, who was struck in the head by a pitch and died a few hours later, became the only MLB player to die of an on-field injury.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Both leagues quickly began to require the use of new, white baseballs whenever a ball became scuffed or dirty, helping bring the "dead-ball" era to an end.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The following year, the New York Yankees made their first World Series appearance.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] By the end of the 1930s, the team had appeared in 11 World Series, winning eight of them.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Yankees slugger Babe Ruth had set the single-season home run record in 1927, hitting 60 home runs; breaking his own record of 29 home runs.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Impacted negatively by the Great Depression, baseball's popularity had begun a downward turn in the early 1930s.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] By 1932, only two MLB teams turned a profit.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Attendance had fallen, due at least in part to a 10% federal amusement tax added to baseball ticket prices.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball owners cut their rosters from 25 men to 23, and even the best players took pay cuts.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Team executives were innovative in their attempts to survive, creating night games, broadcasting games live by radio, and rolling out promotions such as free admission for women.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Throughout the Great Depression, no MLB teams moved or folded.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The onset of World War II created a shortage of professional baseball players, as more than 500 men left MLB teams to serve in the military.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Many of them played on service baseball teams that entertained military personnel in the US or in the Pacific.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB teams of this time largely consisted of young men, older players, and those with a military classification of 4F, indicating mental, physical, or moral unsuitability for service.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Men like Pete Gray, a one-armed outfielder, got the chance to advance to the major leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] However, MLB rosters did not include any black players through the end of the war.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Black players, many of whom served in the war, were still restricted to playing Negro league baseball.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Wartime blackout restrictions, designed to keep outdoor lighting at low levels, caused another problem for baseball.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] These rules limited traveling and night games to the point that the 1942 season was nearly canceled.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] On January 14, 1942, MLB commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis wrote to U.S. president Franklin D.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Roosevelt, pleading for the continuation of baseball during the war.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Roosevelt responded, "I honestly feel that it would be best for the country to keep baseball going.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] There will be fewer people unemployed and everybody will work longer hours and harder than ever before.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] With President Roosevelt's approval, spring training began in 1942 with few repercussions.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The war interrupted the careers of stars including Stan Musial, Bob Feller, Ted Williams, and Joe DiMaggio, but baseball clubs continued to field their teams.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Branch Rickey, president and general manager of the Brooklyn Dodgers, began making efforts to introduce a black baseball player to the previously all-white professional baseball leagues in the mid-1940s.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] He selected Jackie Robinson from a list of promising Negro league players.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] After obtaining a commitment from Robinson to "turn the other cheek" to any racial antagonism directed at him, Rickey agreed to sign him to a contract for $600 a month (equivalent to $9,906 in 2025).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In what was later referred to as "The Noble Experiment", Robinson was the first black baseball player in the International League since the 1880s, joining the Dodgers' farm club, the Montreal Royals, for the 1946 season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The following year, the Dodgers called up Robinson to the major leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] On April 15, 1947, Robinson made his major league debut at Ebbets Field before a crowd of 26,623 spectators, including more than 14,000 black patrons.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Black baseball fans began flocking to see the Dodgers when they came to town, abandoning the Negro league teams that they had followed exclusively.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Robinson's promotion met a generally positive, although mixed, reception among newspaper writers and white major league players.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Manager Leo Durocher informed his team, "I don't care if he is yellow or black or has stripes like a fucking zebra.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] After a strike threat by some players, NL president Ford C.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Frick and Commissioner Happy Chandler let it be known that any striking players would be suspended.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Robinson received significant encouragement from several major-league players, including Dodgers teammate Pee Wee Reese who said, "You can hate a man for many reasons.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Color is not one of them." That year, Robinson won the inaugural Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award (separate NL and AL Rookie of the Year honors were not awarded until 1949).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Less than three months later, Larry Doby became the first African-American to break the color barrier in the American League with the Cleveland Indians.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The next year, a number of other black players entered the major leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Satchel Paige was signed by the Indians and the Dodgers added star catcher Roy Campanella and Don Newcombe, who was later the first winner of the Cy Young Award for his outstanding pitching.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB banned the signing of women to contracts in 1952, but that ban was lifted in 1992.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] There have been no female MLB players since then.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1903 to 1952, the major leagues consisted of two eight-team leagues whose 16 teams were located in ten cities, all in the northeastern and mid-western United States: New York City had three teams and Boston, Chicago, Philadelphia, and St.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis was the southernmost and westernmost city with a major league team.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The longest possible road trip, from Boston to St.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] After a half-century of stability, starting in the 1950s, teams began to move out of cities with multiple teams into cities that had not had them before.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1953 to 1955, three teams moved to new cities: the Boston Braves became the Milwaukee Braves, the St.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis Browns became the Baltimore Orioles, and the Philadelphia Athletics became the Kansas City Athletics.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1958 season began to turn Major League Baseball into a nationwide league.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Walter O'Malley, owner of the Brooklyn Dodgers and "perhaps the most influential owner of baseball's early expansion era", moved his team to Los Angeles, marking the first major league franchise on the West Coast.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] O'Malley also helped persuade the rival New York Giants to move west to become the San Francisco Giants.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Giants owner Horace Stoneham had been contemplating a move to Minnesota amid slumping attendance at the aging Polo Grounds ballpark when O'Malley invited him to meet San Francisco mayor George Christopher in New York.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] After Stoneham was persuaded to move to California, *Time* magazine put O'Malley on its cover.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Frick had opposed the meeting, but the dual moves proved successful for both franchises and for MLB.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Had the Dodgers moved out west alone, the St.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals—1,600 mi (2,575 km) away—would have been the closest NL team.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Instead, the joint move made West Coast road trips economical for visiting teams.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The Dodgers set a single-game MLB attendance record in their first home appearance with 78,672 fans.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1961, the first Washington Senators franchise moved to Minneapolis–Saint Paul to become the Minnesota Twins.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Two new teams were added to the American League at the same time: the Los Angeles Angels (who soon moved from downtown L.A. to nearby Anaheim) and a new Washington Senators franchise.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The NL added the Houston Astros and the New York Mets in 1962.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The Astros (known as the "Colt .45s" during their first three seasons) became the first southern major league franchise since the Louisville Colonels folded in 1899 and the first franchise to be located along the Gulf Coast.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1966, the major leagues moved to the "Deep South" when the Milwaukee Braves moved to Atlanta.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1968, the Kansas City Athletics moved west to become the Oakland Athletics.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1969, the American and National Leagues both added two expansion franchises.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The American League added the Seattle Pilots (who became the Milwaukee Brewers after one disastrous season in Seattle) and the Kansas City Royals.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The NL added the first Canadian franchise, the Montreal Expos, as well as the San Diego Padres.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1972, the second Washington Senators moved to the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex to become the Texas Rangers.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1977, baseball expanded again, adding a second Canadian team, the Toronto Blue Jays, as well as the Seattle Mariners.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Subsequently, no new teams were added until 1993, and no teams moved until 2005.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] By the late 1960s, the balance between pitching and hitting had swung in favor of the pitchers.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1968—later nicknamed "the year of the pitcher"—Boston Red Sox player Carl Yastrzemski won the American League batting title with an average of just .301, the lowest in MLB history.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Detroit Tigers pitcher Denny McLain won 31 games, making him the only pitcher to win 30 games in a season since Dizzy Dean in 1934.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals starting pitcher Bob Gibson achieved an equally remarkable feat by allowing an ERA of just 1.12.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Following these pitching performances, in December 1968 the MLB Playing Rules Committee voted to reduce the strike zone from knees to shoulders to top of knees to armpits and lower the pitcher's mound from 15 to 10 inches, beginning in the 1969 season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1973, the American League, which had been suffering from much lower attendance than the National League, sought to increase scoring even further by initiating the designated hitter (DH) rule.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Throughout the 1960s and 1970s, as baseball expanded, the National Football League (NFL) had been surging in popularity, making it economical for many of these cities to build multi-purpose stadiums instead of single-purpose baseball fields.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Because of climate and economic issues, many of these facilities had playing surfaces made from artificial turf, as well as the oval designs characteristic of stadiums designed to house both baseball and football.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] This often resulted in baseball fields with relatively more foul territory than older stadiums.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] These characteristics changed the nature of professional baseball, putting a higher premium on speed and defense over home-run hitting power since the fields were often too big for teams to expect to hit many home runs and foul balls hit in the air could more easily be caught for outs.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Teams began to be built around pitching—particularly their bullpens—and speed on the basepaths.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Artificial surfaces meant balls traveled quicker and bounced higher, so it became easier to hit ground balls "in the hole" between the corner and middle infielders.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Starting pitchers were no longer expected to throw complete games; it was enough for a starter to pitch 6–7 innings and turn the game over to the team's closer, a position which grew in importance over these decades.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] As stolen bases increased, home run totals dropped.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] After Willie Mays hit 52 home runs in 1965, only one player (George Foster) reached that mark until the 1990s.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] During the 1980s, baseball experienced a number of significant changes the game had not seen in years.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Home runs were on the decline throughout the decade, with players hitting 40 home runs just 13 times and no one hitting more than 50 home runs in a season for the first time since the dead-ball era (1900–1919).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1981 MLB strike from June 12 until July 31 forced the cancellation of 713 games and resulted in a split-season format.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1985, Pete Rose broke Ty Cobb's all-time hits record with his 4,192nd hit.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1989, Rose received a lifetime ban from baseball as a result of betting on baseball games while manager of the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Rose was the first person to receive a lifetime ban from baseball since 1943.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] 1985 also saw the Pittsburgh drug trials which involved players who were called to testify before a grand jury in Pittsburgh related to cocaine trafficking.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1994–95 MLB strike from August 12, 1994, to April 25, 1995, caused the cancellation of over 900 games and the forfeit of the entire 1994 postseason.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Routinely in the late 1990s and early 2000s, baseball players hit 40 or 50 home runs in a season, a feat that was considered rare even in the 1980s.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] It later became apparent that at least some of this power surge was a result of players using steroids and other performance-enhancing drugs.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1993, the National League added the Florida Marlins in Miami and the Colorado Rockies in Denver.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1998, the Brewers switched leagues by joining the National League, and two new teams were added: the National League's Arizona Diamondbacks in Phoenix and the American League's Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] After the 2001 season, the team owners voted in favor of contraction.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Several MLB teams had been considered for elimination in early talks about contraction, but the Montreal Expos and the Minnesota Twins were the two teams that came closest to folding under the plan.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Plans for MLB contraction were halted when the Twins landlord was awarded a court injunction that required the team to play its 2002 home games at their stadium.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB owners agreed to hold off on reducing the league's size until at least 2006.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The Montreal Expos became the first franchise in over three decades to move when they became the Washington Nationals in 2005.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] This move left Canada with just one team, but it also returned baseball to Washington after a 33-year absence.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] This franchise shift, like many previous ones, involved baseball's return to a city that had been previously abandoned.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In recent years, with the advent of technologies such as Statcast and its use of Hawk-Eye starting in 2020 as well as with advanced statistics as provided by sites such as FanGraphs and Baseball Savant, MLB has evolved.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] With the ability to see precise movements of pitchers and batters, teams can assess the mechanics of a player and help them improve.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Statcast also provides some features such as tracking the paths of most batted balls, tracking the speed of most batted balls, and tracking the exit velocity of most batted balls.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Statcast has allowed for advanced defensive analytics that have not been possible before tracking of players due to how subjective fielding can be.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The rate of teams using a defensive shift went up from 13.7% in 2016 to 33.6% in 2022 because advanced statistics supported this as an effective way to stop hitters from getting hits.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Because the shift reduces the number of balls in play that result in hits and MLB wishes to increase interest in baseball, MLB announced in September 2022 that extreme infield defensive shifts would be banned starting in 2023.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] To be compliant, there must be two fielders on each side of second base, and those fielders must have both of their feet on the infield dirt at the time the pitch is thrown.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] If this rule is not followed, the choice of an automatic ball or the outcome of the play is given to the batting team.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The game of baseball has also slowed down significantly due to an increased number of strikeouts and walks—two outcomes that generally take many pitches to complete—and an increased amount of time taken for a pitcher to pitch.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2020, it took an average of three hours and six minutes to complete a 9 inning game, a number which has steadily ticked up for years.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Along with the restrictions on defensive shifts, MLB announced the introduction of a pitch clock for the 2023 season and beyond, which is something that has been an experiment in MiLB for a few years.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] By the time the clock reaches 10 seconds, the catcher must be in their crouch behind home plate.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] When the clock reaches 8 seconds, the batter must be in the batter's box and be "alert".
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Before the 15 second timer reaches 0 seconds, the pitcher must have started their "motion to pitch".
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] If any of these deadlines are violated, the count of the batter will be increased by one ball if the defending team violated the pitch clock or one strike if it is the offensive team who violated the pitch clock.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Additionally, in order to prevent circumventing these rules, pickoffs and step-offs — which reset the pitch clock — are only allowed two times total per plate appearance, and if a pitcher attempts a third pickoff and fails to get the runner out, a ball will be called.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Similarly, a batter is restricted to calling a timeout (an action which resets the pitch clock) just once per plate appearance.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2019, MLB opened an investigation into allegations that members of the 2017 World Series champion Houston Astros stole signs from opposing teams using technology during the 2017 and 2018 seasons.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The Astros were found guilty in January 2020 and while no active players faced any repercussions due to an immunity agreement in exchange for testimony, Astros general manager Jeff Luhnow and field manager A.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Hinch were suspended for the entire 2020 season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The Astros were fined the maximum allowable $5 million and forfeited their first- and second-round picks in the 2020 and 2021 drafts.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The Boston Red Sox were also found guilty of stealing signs during the 2017 and 2018 seasons, with the latter season ending in a World Series victory.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Red Sox manager Alex Cora was suspended for a year and the team was fined with the loss of a second-round draft pick in the 2020 draft as a result.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In November 2023, the Oakland Athletics relocation to Las Vegas was approved by MLB owners.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] They are to play the 2025 through 2027 seasons in West Sacramento, California, while a new stadium is built in the Las Vegas metropolitan area, and will be referred to as simply the "Athletics" and "A's", with no city name attached.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB has discussed preparations for another round of expansion, and several investment groups are vying for a franchise.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2025, commissioner Rob Manfred said MLB could add two teams and pursue a geographic realignment of its leagues and divisions.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB is governed by the Major League Baseball Constitution.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] This document has undergone several incarnations since its creation in 1876.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Under the direction of the commissioner of baseball, MLB hires and maintains the sport's umpiring crews, and negotiates marketing, labor, and television contracts.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB maintains a unique, controlling relationship over the sport, including most aspects of Minor League Baseball.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] This is due in large part to the 1922 U.S.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Supreme Court ruling in *Federal Baseball Club v.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] National League*, which held that baseball is not interstate commerce and therefore not subject to federal antitrust law; MLB is the only league that has such a status, and has not faced any competition since this case.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] This ruling has been weakened only slightly in subsequent years.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The weakened ruling granted more stability to the owners of teams and has resulted in values increasing at double-digit rates.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] There were several challenges to MLB's primacy in the sport, with notable attempts to establish competing leagues occurring during the late 1800s, from 1913 to 1915 with the short-lived Federal League, and in 1960 with the aborted Continental League.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The chief executive of MLB is the commissioner, Rob Manfred.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The deputy commissioner of baseball administration and chief legal officer is Dan Halem.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The multimedia branch of MLB is MLB Advanced Media, which is based in New York City.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] This branch oversees MLB.com and each of the 30 teams' websites.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Its charter states that MLB Advanced Media holds editorial independence from the league, but it is under the same ownership group and revenue-sharing plan.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB Productions is a similarly structured wing of the league, focusing on video and traditional broadcast media.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB also owns 67 percent of MLB Network, with the other 33 percent split between several cable operators and satellite provider DirecTV.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] It operates out of studios in Secaucus, New Jersey, and also has editorial independence from the league.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1920, the weak National Commission, created to manage relationships between the two leagues, was replaced with the much more powerful commissioner of baseball, who had the power to make decisions for all of professional baseball unilaterally.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1901 to 1960, the American League and National League fielded eight teams apiece.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In the 1960s, MLB expansion added eight teams, including the first non-U.S. team (the Montreal Expos).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Two teams (the Seattle Mariners and the Toronto Blue Jays) were also added in the 1970s.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1969 through 1993, each league consisted of an East and West Division.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1993, the National League expanded with two teams, the Florida Marlins and the Colorado Rockies, to even up the number of teams in both leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] A third division, the Central Division, was formed in each league in 1994.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Until 1996, the two leagues met on the field only during the World Series and the All-Star Game.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In March 1995, two new franchises, the Arizona Diamondbacks and Tampa Bay Devil Rays (now known as the Tampa Bay Rays), were awarded by MLB, which began play in 1998.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] This addition brought the total number of franchises to 30.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In early 1997, MLB decided to assign one new team to each league: Tampa Bay joined the AL and Arizona joined the NL.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The original plan was to have an odd number of teams in each league (15 per league, with five in each division), but in order for every team to be able to play daily, this would have required interleague play to be scheduled throughout the entire season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] However, it was unclear at the time if the interleague play would continue after the 1998 season, as it had to be approved by the players' union.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] For this and other reasons, it was decided that both leagues should continue to have an even number of teams, and therefore, one existing club would have to switch leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed in November 1997 to move from the AL to the NL, thereby making the AL a 14-team league and the NL a 16-team league.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers agreed to move from the AL East to the AL Central (to replace Milwaukee), with the expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays joining the AL East.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Later, when the Houston Astros changed ownership prior to the 2013 season, the team moved from the NL Central to the AL West, resulting in both leagues having three divisions of five teams each and allowing all teams to have a more balanced schedule.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Interleague play is now held throughout the season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2000, the AL and NL were dissolved as legal entities, and MLB became a single, overall league *de jure*, similar to the National Football League (NFL), National Basketball Association (NBA) and National Hockey League (NHL)—albeit with two components called "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The use of "major-league baseball" to refer to the overall AL–NL construct prior to 2000 is preferred, since statements such as "In 1942, Ted Williams led MLB with 36 homers, 137 RBIs, a .356 batting average, and won the first of his two Triple Crowns" are anachronistic.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Since becoming a single entity, common rules and regulations have been used in both MLB leagues, with one former exception: the AL continued operating under the designated hitter (DH) rule, while the NL did not.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2020, the NL used the DH rule for the first time.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] As part of the settlement of the 2021–22 Major League Baseball lockout, this change was made permanent, thus making the rules in the two leagues identical.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] A baseball uniform is a type of uniform worn by baseball players and by some non-playing personnel, such as field managers and coaches.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] It is worn to indicate the person's role in the game and—through the use of logos, colors, and numbers—to identify the teams and their players, managers, and coaches.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Traditionally, home uniforms display the team name on the front, while away uniforms display the team's home location.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In modern times, however, exceptions to this pattern have become common, with teams using their team name on both uniforms.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Most teams also have one or more alternate uniforms, usually consisting of the primary or secondary team color on the vest instead of the usual white or gray.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In the past few decades throwback uniforms have become popular.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] The New York Knickerbockers were the first baseball team to use uniforms, taking the field on April 4, 1849, in pants made of blue wool, white flannel shirts (jerseys) and straw hats.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Caps and other types of headgear have been a part of baseball uniforms from the beginning.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball teams often wore full-brimmed straw hats or no cap at all since there was no official rule regarding headgear.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] Under the 1882 uniform rules, players on the same team wore uniforms of different colors and patterns that indicated which position they played.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] This rule was soon abandoned as impractical.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In the late 1880s, Detroit and Washington of the National League and Brooklyn of the American Association were the first to wear striped uniforms.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] By the end of the 19th century, teams began the practice of having two different uniforms, one for when they played at home in their own baseball stadium and a different one for when they played away (on the road) at the other team's ballpark.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] It became common to wear white pants with a white color vest at home and gray pants with a gray or solid (dark) colored vest when away.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] By 1900, both home and away uniforms were standard across the major leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] In June 2021, MLB announced a long-term deal with cryptocurrency exchange FTX, which includes the FTX logo appearing on umpire uniforms during all games.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] FTX is MLB's first-ever umpire uniform patch partner.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] On November 11, 2022, FTX filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB removed the FTX patches from umpires' uniforms before the 2023 season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Spring training is a series of practices and exhibition games preceding the start of the regular season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Teams hold training camps in the states of Arizona and Florida, where the early warm weather allows teams to practice and play without worrying about the late winter cold.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Spring training allows new players to compete for roster and position spots and gives existing team players practice time prior to competitive play.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The teams that hold spring training in Arizona are grouped into the Cactus League, while teams that hold camp in Florida are known as the Grapefruit League.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Spring training typically lasts almost two months, starting in mid-February and running until just before the season-opening day, traditionally the first week of April.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] As pitchers benefit from a longer training period, pitchers and catchers begin spring training several days before the rest of the team.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] A team's schedule is typically organized into three-game series, sets of consecutive games against the same opponent, with occasional two- or four-game series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Postponed games or continuations of suspended games can result in an ad hoc one-game or five-game series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] All games of a series are usually hosted by the same team, and multiple series are typically grouped together.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] I.e, a team usually hosts several series in a row, called a homestand, and follows that by going on several road series in a row.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Teams generally play games five to seven days per week.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Most games are scheduled at night, although teams will often play day games on Opening Day, holidays, and for the last game of a series to allow teams extra time to travel to their next opponent.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Sunday games are generally played during the afternoon, allowing teams to travel to their next destination prior to a Monday night game.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In the current three-division structure, each team plays 13 games against each of its four divisional opponents.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] It plays one home series and one away series, amounting to six or seven games, against the 10 other teams in its league.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] A team also plays 3-game series with all the other teams in the other league, alternating home teams each year.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Furthermore, each team has an interleague "natural rival" (in some cases its counterpart in the same metro area) with which it plays three home games and three away games each year.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] With an odd number of teams in each league (15), it is necessary to have two teams participate in interleague play for most days in the season, except when two or more teams have a day off.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] From 2013 to 2022, each team played 20 interleague games throughout the season, usually with just one interleague game per day, but for one weekend in late May, all teams would participate in an interleague series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] (Season-long interleague play was not necessary before 2013 as each league had an even number of teams.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2013, the Houston Astros moved to the American League, so that each league would have 15 teams.) Prior to the adoption of the universal designated hitter in 2022, whether the DH was in use depended on whether the home team was from the AL, where the DH was used, or the NL, where it was not.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the 2023 season, the scheduling formula changed, with each team playing at least one series against every other team every year.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Beginning with the 2022 season, teams compete for the six playoff berths in their respective leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] To secure a berth, a team must either win its division or capture a wild card spot by having one of the three best records among the non-winners in its entire league.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] With the adoption of a third wild card, the former practice of breaking ties with an additional regular-season game, known as Game 163, was dropped in favor of a tie-breaker formula.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In early-to-mid July, just after the midway point of the season, the Major League Baseball All-Star Game is held during a four-day break from the regular-season schedule.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The All-Star Game features a team of players from the American League (AL)—led by the manager of the previous AL World Series team—and a team of players from the National League (NL), similarly managed, in an exhibition game.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] From 1959 to 1962, two games were held each season, one was held in July and one was held in August.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The designated-hitter rule was used in the All-Star Game for the first time in 1989.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Following games used a DH when the game was played in an AL ballpark.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2010, the DH rule has been in effect regardless of venue.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The first official All-Star Game was held as part of the 1933 World's Fair in Chicago, Illinois, and was the idea of Arch Ward, then sports editor for *The Chicago Tribune*.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Initially intended to be a one-time event, its great success resulted in making the game an annual one.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Ward's contribution was recognized by Major League Baseball in 1962 with the creation of the "Arch Ward Trophy", given to the All-Star Game's Most Valuable Player each year.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] (In 1970, it was renamed the Commissioner's Trophy, until 1985, when the name change was reversed.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Beginning in 1947, the eight position players in each team's starting lineup have been voted into the game by fans.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The fan voting was discontinued after a 1957 ballot-box-stuffing scandal in Cincinnati: seven of the eight slots originally went to Reds players, two of whom were subsequently removed from the lineup to make room for Willie Mays and Hank Aaron.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Fan voting was reinstated in 1970 and has continued ever since, including internet voting in recent years.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The 2002 contest in Milwaukee controversially ended in an 11-inning tie when both managers ran out of pitchers.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In response, starting in 2003 the league which wins the All-Star game received home-field advantage in the World Series: the league champion hosted the first two games at its own ballpark as well as the last two (if necessary).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The National League did not win an All-Star game and thus gain a home-field advantage until 2010; it was able to overcome this disadvantage and win in three of the seven World Series from 2003 to 2009.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] This was discontinued after the 2016 season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB All-Stars from both leagues have worn uniforms from their respective teams at the game with one exception.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In the 1933 All-Star Game, the National League All-Star Team members wore special gray uniforms with "National League" written in navy blue letters across the front of the jersey.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The regular season ends after the first Sunday in October (or the last Sunday in September), after which twelve teams enter the postseason playoffs.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] These twelve teams consist of the six division champions and six "wild-card" teams: the team with the best overall win–loss record in each of the six divisions, and the three teams in each league with the best records other than the division champions.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] American League Division Series and National League Division Series, each a best-of-five-games series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] American League Championship Series and National League Championship Series, each a best-of-seven-games series played between the winning teams from the Division Series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The league champions are referred to as the pennant winners.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] World Series, a best-of-seven-games series played between the pennant winners of each league.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Within each league, the division winners are the 1, 2, and 3-seeds, based on win–loss records.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The teams with the first, second, and third best records among non-division winners will be seeded 4, 5, and 6 respectively.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Throughout the postseason, home-field advantage is awarded to the team with the higher win-loss record, with tiebreakers being applied if necessary.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Wild Card Series, the 3-seed will host the 6-seed, and the 4-seed will host the 5-seed, with the winners advancing to the Division Series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Unlike the NFL, there is no reseeding between each series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Division Series, the 1-seed goes up against the 4/5-seed and the 2-seed goes up against the 3/6-seed.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The winners of those matches will compete in their respective League Championship Series for their league pennant, and the pennant winners will advance to the World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2017, home-field advantage in the World Series is determined by regular-season records of the two league champions, replacing a system used for the prior 14 seasons where the champion of the league that won the All-Star Game would receive home-field advantage.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] With this format, the home-field advantage does not usually play a large role in the postseason unless the series goes to its maximum number of games.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] However, because the first two games of a postseason series are hosted by the same team, a team starting with two wins will likely have momentum heading into the venue switch.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] From 1986 to 2018, an MLB All-Star team was sent to a biennial end-of-the-season tour of Japan, dubbed the MLB Japan All-Star Series, playing exhibition games in a best-of format against the All-Stars from Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB) or, in 2014 and 2018, their national team, Samurai Japan.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB played the MLB China Series in the People's Republic of China.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] It was a series of two spring-training games between the San Diego Padres and Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The games were an effort to popularize baseball in China.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB played the MLB Taiwan All-Star Series in Taiwan in November 2011.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] It was a series of five exhibition games played by a team made up of MLB players called the MLB All-Stars and the Chinese Taipei national baseball team.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The MLB All-Stars swept the series, five games to zero.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] At the end of the 2011 season, it was announced that the Seattle Mariners and the Oakland Athletics would play their season openers in Japan.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In October 2013, Phil Rogers of the *Chicago Tribune* wrote that MLB was considering postseason all-star tours in Taiwan and Korea; baseball is increasing in popularity in both countries.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The Arizona Diamondbacks opened the 2014 season against Los Angeles Dodgers from March 22–23 in Australia.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The teams played each other at the historic Sydney Cricket Ground, which has a seating capacity of 46,000.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The two games represented the first MLB regular-season play held in that country.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The games counted as home games for the Diamondbacks, so they played 79 home games at Chase Field.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2019, the Boston Red Sox were the home team in a regular-season two-game series against the New York Yankees.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The games, which were the first regular-season MLB games held in Europe, were played on June 29–30 at London Stadium with the Yankees winning both games.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The San Diego Padres and Los Angeles Dodgers opened the 2024 regular season on March 20–21 at Gocheok Sky Dome in Seoul, South Korea.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The ceremonial first pitch of the opening game was thrown by the first Korean-born MLB player Chan Ho Park, who made his debut with the LA Dodgers in 1994.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The two-game Seoul Series resulted in a split between the two teams.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] There were also four exhibition games played during March 17–18, where the Dodgers took on the Kiwoom Heroes and Team Korea, and the Padres faced the LG Twins and Team Korea.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The 2025 season began with the Los Angeles Dodgers and the Chicago Cubs playing in Tokyo at the Tokyo Dome for the MLB Tokyo Series 2025.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Together with the World Baseball Softball Confederation, MLB sponsors the World Baseball Classic, an international baseball tournament contested by national teams.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In 1998, both Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa hit more home runs than the record of 61 set by Yankees right fielder Roger Maris in 1961.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Barry Bonds topped the record in 2001 with 73 home runs.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] McGwire, Bonds, and Sosa became the subjects of speculation regarding the use of performance-enhancing substances.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] McGwire later admitted that he used a steroid hormone that was still legal in baseball during the 1998 season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Baseball's original steroid testing policy, in effect from 2002 to 2005, provided for penalties ranging from a ten-game suspension for a first positive test to a one-year suspension for a fourth positive test.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Players were tested at least once per year, with the chance that several players could be tested many times per year.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell was appointed by Selig on March 30, 2006 to investigate the use of performance-enhancing drugs in MLB.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The appointment was made after several influential members of the U.S.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Congress made negative comments about both the effectiveness and honesty of MLB's drug policies and Commissioner Selig.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] It pointed out that HGH is likely a placebo with no performance-enhancing effects.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The report included substance use allegations against at least one player from each MLB team.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] According to ESPN, some people questioned whether Mitchell's director role with the Boston Red Sox created a conflict of interest, especially because no "prime [Sox] players were in the report".
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The report named several prominent Yankees who were parts of World Series clubs; there is a long-running and fierce Yankees–Red Sox rivalry.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Dowd brought up Mitchell's conflict of interest, but he later said that the former senator had done a good job.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Mitchell acknowledged that his "tight relationship with Major League Baseball left him open to criticism", but he said that readers who examine the report closely "will not find any evidence of bias, of special treatment of the Red Sox".
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] On January 10, 2013, MLB and the players union reached an agreement to add random, in-season HGH testing.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] They also agreed to implement a new test to reveal the use of testosterone for the 2013 season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The current MLB drug policy provides for an 80-game suspension for a first positive test, a 162-game suspension for a second positive test, and a lifetime suspension for a third positive test.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2009, allegations surfaced against Alex Rodriguez and David Ortiz, and Manny Ramirez received a 50-game suspension after testing positive for banned substances.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In early April 2011, Ramirez retired from baseball rather than face a 100-game suspension for his second positive steroid test.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] He would later unretire, having the suspension dropped to 50 games, and would serve those in 2012.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting in 2026, Fox, ESPN, NBC, TBS, and MLB Network will nationally televise MLB games in the United States.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox has been MLB's primary broadcast television partner since 1996.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2008, Fox has broadcast MLB games on Saturdays throughout the entire season; Fox previously only broadcast games from May to September.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox also holds rights to the All-Star Game each season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox also alternates League Championship Series broadcasts, broadcasting the American League Championship Series (ALCS) in odd-numbered years and the National League Championship Series (NLCS) in even-numbered years.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox broadcasts all games of the World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN has been MLB's cable television partner since 1990.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The network has aired the weekly regular season game *Sunday Night Baseball* and postseason broadcasts of the Wild Card Series exclusively.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] TBS began airing Sunday afternoon regular season games (non-exclusive) nationally in 2008, which was then replaced by Tuesday night games in 2022.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] From 2007 to 2020, TBS had its exclusive rights to any tiebreaker games that determine division or wild card champions.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] It also airs exclusive coverage of the Division Series round of the playoffs.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] TBS carries the League Championship Series that are not included under Fox's television agreement; TBS shows the NLCS in odd-numbered years and the ALCS in even-numbered years.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In January 2009, MLB launched MLB Network, featuring news and coverage from around the league, and airing 26 live games in the 2009 season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Each team also has local broadcasts for all games not exclusively carried nationally.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] These games are typically split between a local broadcast television station and a local or regional sports network (RSN), though some teams only air local games through RSNs or through their own team networks.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] As Canada only contains one team, Sportsnet broadcasts Toronto Blue Jays games nationally.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The channel is owned by Rogers Communications, who is also the parent company of the Blue Jays.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Sportsnet also televises Fox's Saturday afternoon games, the All-Star Game, playoff games, and the World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In April 2011, TSN2 began carrying ESPN *Sunday Night Baseball* in Canada.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] TVA Sports airs Blue Jays games in French.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Several MLB games are broadcast exclusively on streaming television.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] After a year of exclusive games on Facebook, MLB partnered with YouTube to stream weekly games on the service beginning in the 2019 season, and extending until 2022.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2022, MLB made a deal with Apple Inc. to launch *Friday Night Baseball* on its Apple TV+ streaming service, and NBC Sports to broadcast *MLB Sunday Leadoff*, a package of early Sunday afternoon games on Peacock.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Since the 2023 season's Division Series, HBO Max began simulcasting games broadcast by its sister network TBS (both owned by Warner Bros.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In the 2024 season, The Roku Channel began streaming *MLB Sunday Leadoff*.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Announced in November 2025, MLB signed three-year media-rights deals with Netflix, ESPN, and NBCUniversal for the 2026 to 2028 seasons.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] A local broadcaster has priority to televise games of the team in their market over national broadcasters if the game is not exclusive to the national broadcaster.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] A market that has a local team playing in a non-exclusive game will receive an alternative programming feed on the national broadcaster.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB's streaming internet video service is also subject to the same blackout rules.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Commissioner Robert Manfred has expressed interest in changing the blackout policy to loosen the rules for streaming options.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The first baseball game ever broadcast on radio was a Pittsburgh Pirates versus Philadelphia Phillies game on August 5, 1921.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The game was broadcast by KDKA of Pittsburgh, and the Pirates defeated the Phillies 8–5.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] It was broadcast by KDKA staff announcer Harold Arlin.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] That year, KDKA and WJZ of Newark broadcast the first World Series on the radio, between the New York Giants and the New York Yankees, with Grantland Rice and Tommy Cowan calling the games for KDKA and WJZ, respectively.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] However, the broadcasters were not actually present at the game, but simply gave reports from a telegraph wire.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In 1922, WJZ broadcast the entire series, with Rice doing play-by-play.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] For the 1923 World Series, Rice was joined on Westinghouse for the first time by Graham McNamee.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] During the 1923 World Series, Rice was the main broadcaster, but during the fourth inning of Game 3, he turned the microphone over to McNamee.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] This was the start of McNamee's career, and McNamee became the first color commentator.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Although frequently criticized for his lack of expertise, McNamee helped popularize baseball.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In 1998, national radio broadcasts moved to ESPN Radio.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN Radio currently broadcasts *Sunday Night Baseball* games during the regular season, as well as Saturday and occasional weekday games, along with the All-Star Game and all postseason contests.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2021, TUDN Radio airs Spanish-language coverage of select regular season and postseason games, including the World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In addition, each team employs its own announcers, who broadcast during the regular season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Most teams operate regional networks to cover their fan bases; some of these supposedly regional networks (such as the New York Yankees Radio Network) have a national reach with affiliates located across the United States.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Major League Baseball has an exclusive rights deal with XM Satellite Radio, which includes the channel MLB Network Radio and live play-by-play of all games.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB games are also broadcast live on the internet.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] All television and radio broadcasts of games are available via subscription to MLB.tv at Major League Baseball's website, MLB.com, and radio-only broadcasts are also available via subscription to MLB.com Gameday Audio.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2026, MLB.tv will be integrated into the ESPN App.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2005, Major League Baseball has a partnership with XM Satellite Radio, launching a 24-7 channel, MLB Home Plate (now MLB Network Radio) which carries every major league game.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Games are also carried on MLB Gameday Audio.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] While all teams maintain a network of stations carrying their games in English, many teams also broadcast their games in Spanish, on a second network.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In addition, when the Washington Nationals were based in Montreal as the Montreal Expos, their games were broadcast in both English and French.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Some Toronto Blue Jays games have been broadcast in French as well.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Selected games of the Los Angeles Dodgers are broadcast in Korean by KMPC.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In modern years, teams have become increasingly reliant on local cable television rights fees, which grew unstable in the 2020s and which are not subject to equal revenue sharing.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Following the Disney-Fox merger, Disney divested Fox's regional broadcasting networks, which covered 14 of MLB's 30 teams, to Diamond Sports Network / Bally Sports.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Diamond filed for bankruptcy in 2023 and took advantage of debtor-friendly rules in the Bankruptcy Code to cancel or renegotiate its TV deals with a third of the league.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Teams that locked themselves into relatively stable deals near the peak of the market found themselves in a stronger financial position relative to the average team than ever before.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Critics respond that industry revenues and team valuations are still rising.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN broadcasts some MLB games in other countries, including ESPN Australia in Australia and New Zealand, ESPN Africa, and ESPN in the Netherlands.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In Mexico, until 2022, Fox Sports aired five regular season games per week and post-season games that belong to the league that broadcasts its American namesake (including the Wild Card Series).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Likewise, TUDN carried 4 matches a week until 2022: through the pay television signal, games were broadcast on Tuesdays and Thursdays, while on Saturdays (generally at 12:00 p.m.) and Sundays (rotating between NBA games, until the start of the NFL season) games were broadcast on Canal 9.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the Championship Series, it only broadcast one division and the whole World Series, these were broadcast on free-to-air television for 59 years.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the 2023 season, Imagen Televisión announced it would begin broadcasting a regular season game every Saturday and Sunday as well as the playoffs and the World Series on open television and its website in Mexico.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In Argentina, Fox Sports carries 5 regular season games per week and post-season games that belong to the league that broadcasts its American namesake (including the Wild Card Series).
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In Venezuela, since the 2016 season the cable channel IVC has the broadcast rights, they currently air 7 games per week.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the 2022 season, Televen broadcasts two games a week and the postseason on free-to-air TV While Venevisión, starting with the 2023 season, would return with the space "El Juego de la Semana" that carries a game every Sunday and non-working days on free-to-air television.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Dominican Republic since 2009 Grupo Altice has broadcast the entire regular season, playoffs and World Series through pay TV while on free-to-air television and radio Grupo Corripio airs 7 games per week and the entire postseason.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In Spain, Movistar Plus+ has the rights to broadcast the entire season, including one game daily, and the postseason, covering all games in the championship series and World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Channel 5 in the United Kingdom previously screened MLB games, including the All-Star Game and postseason games, on Sunday and Wednesday, usually starting at 1 a.m.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Most recently, Johnny Gould and Josh Chetwynd presented *MLB on Five* on that station.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] The channel covered baseball beginning on its opening night in 1997, but for financial reasons, the decision was made not to pick up MLB for the 2009 season.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] BT Sport ESPN show live and recorded games several times a week—it is available with BT Sport and (on a subscriber-basis) Virgin Media in the UK.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN America televised many games in the UK and dozens of other countries; in May 2013, ESPN announced that it would shut down the channel on July 31, 2013.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Middle East, North Africa and France, MLB games are broadcast on beIN Sports channels.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] In Germany, Austria and Switzerland, as many as 500 MLB games will be broadcast from 2022 exclusively on the Sport1 platforms until 2026.
[src:freeman-brown/major-league-baseball-p02] Sport1 also broadcasts MLB games in Hungary, as of 2025.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The **National League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **National League** (**NL**), is the older of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada, and the world's oldest extant professional team sports league.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The National League survived competition from various other professional baseball leagues during the late 19th century.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Most did not last for more than a few seasons, with a handful of teams joining the NL once their leagues folded.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The American League declared itself a second major league in 1901, and the AL and NL engaged in a "baseball war" during 1901 and 1902 before agreeing to a "peace pact" that recognized each other as legitimate "major leagues".
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] As part of this agreement, the leagues agreed to respect player contracts, establish rules about relationships with minor league clubs, and allow their champions to meet in a "World Series" to decide the overall professional baseball championship.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] National League teams have won 53 of the 121 World Series championships contested from 1903 to 2025.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and most of the playoffs, with only their champions facing off in the World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] This separation gradually caused the leagues to develop slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The National League was long considered the more "traditional" league, a reputation most exemplified by the NL's more prevalent use of "smallball" tactics and lack of a designated hitter rule, which the AL implemented in 1973.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] However, with the advent of free agency in the 1970s allowing for more player movement between leagues, and the introduction of regular season interleague play in 1997, the difference in play between the two major leagues has diminished considerably.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The NL's adoption of the designated hitter rule in 2022, and the expansion of interleague play to 46 games beginning in 2023, has further blurred the lines between leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate legal and business entities with their own president and management.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the National League legally merged with the American League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which has since operated much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Hulbert (1832–1882), a Chicago businessman and an officer of the Chicago White Stockings of 1870–1889, approached several NA clubs with the plans for a professional league for the sport of baseball with a stronger central authority and exclusive territories in larger cities only.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Additionally, Hulbert had a problem: five of his star players were threatened with expulsion from the NAPBBP because Hulbert had signed them to his club using what were considered questionable means.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Hulbert had a great vested interest in creating his own league, and after recruiting St.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Louis privately, four western clubs met in Louisville, Kentucky, in January 1876.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The National League's formation meant the end of the old National Association after only five seasons, as its remaining clubs shut down or reverted to amateur or minor league status.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The only strong club from 1875 excluded in 1876 was a second one in Philadelphia, often called the White Stockings or later Phillies.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The first game in National League history was played on April 22, 1876, at Philadelphia's Jefferson Street Grounds, at 25th & Jefferson Streets, between the Philadelphia Athletics and the Boston baseball club.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The new league's authority was soon tested after the first season.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The Athletic and Mutual clubs fell behind in the standings and refused to make western road trips late in the season, preferring to play games against local non-league competition to recoup some of their financial losses rather than travel extensively incurring more costs.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The National League operated with only six clubs during 1877 and 1878.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Over the next several years, various teams joined and left the struggling league.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] By 1880, six of the eight charter members had folded.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The two remaining original NL franchises, Boston and Chicago, remain still in operation today as the Atlanta Braves and the Chicago Cubs.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 1883, new New York and Philadelphia clubs began National League play.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Both teams remain in the NL today, the Phillies in their original city and the New York franchise (later named Giants) now in San Francisco since 1958.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The NL encountered its first strong rival organization when the American Association began play in 1882.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The AA played in cities where the NL did not have teams, offered Sunday games and alcoholic beverages in locales where permitted, and sold cheaper tickets everywhere (25 cents versus the NL's standard 50 cents, a hefty sum for many in 1882).
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The NL struck back by establishing new clubs in 1883 in AA cities Philadelphia (later called "Phillies") and New York (the team that would become the Giants).
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The National League and the American Association participated in a version of the World Series seven times during their ten-year coexistence.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] These contests were less organized than the modern Series, lasting as few as three games and as many as fifteen, with two Series (1885 and 1890) ending in disputed ties.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The NL won four times and the AA only once, in 1886.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Starting with the Pittsburgh Pirates in 1887, the National League began to raid the American Association for franchises to replace NL teams that folded.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Other new leagues that rose to compete with the National League were the Union Association and the Players' League.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The Union Association was established in 1884 and folded after playing only one season, its league champion St.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The Players' League was established in 1890 by the Brotherhood of Professional Base-Ball Players, the sport's first players' union, which had failed to persuade the NL to modify its labor practices, including a salary cap and a reserve clause that bound players to their teams indefinitely.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The NL suffered many defections of star players to the Players' League, but the P.L. collapsed after one season.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The Brooklyn, Chicago, Pittsburgh, and New York franchises of the NL absorbed their Players' League counterparts.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The labor strike of 1890 hastened the downfall of the American Association.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] After the 1891 season, the AA disbanded and merged with the NL, which became known legally for the next decade as the "National League and American Association".
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The teams now known as the Cincinnati Reds, Los Angeles Dodgers (originally Brooklyn) and Pittsburgh Pirates (as well as the now-defunct Cleveland Spiders) had already switched from the AA to the NL prior to 1892.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] With the merger, the NL absorbed the St.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Louis Cardinals), along with three other teams that did not survive into the 20th century—the Baltimore Orioles (not the current MLB team), Louisville Colonels, and Washington Statesmen.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] While four teams that moved from the AA remain in the NL today (Pittsburgh [1887], Cincinnati [1890], Los Angeles [originally Brooklyn; 1890], and St.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Louis [1892]), only two original NL franchises (1876) remain in the league: the Chicago Cubs and the Atlanta Braves (originally in Boston, and later Milwaukee).
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The Cubs are the only charter member to play continuously in the same city.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The other two pre-1892 teams still in the league are the Philadelphia Phillies and the San Francisco Giants (originally New York), both of which joined in 1883.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The National League became a 12-team circuit with monopoly status for the rest of the decade.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The league became embroiled in numerous internal conflicts, not the least of which was a plan supported by some owners (and bitterly opposed by others) to form a "trust", wherein there would be one common ownership of all twelve teams.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The NL used its monopsony power to force a $2,400 ($89,000 today) limit on annual player wages in 1894.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] As the 20th century dawned, the NL was in trouble.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Conduct among players was poor, and fistfights were a common sight at games.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In addition to fighting each other, they fought with the umpires and often filled the air at games with foul language and obscenities.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] A game between the Orioles and Boston Beaneaters (a precursor to today's Atlanta Braves) in 1894 ended up having tragic consequences when players became engaged in a brawl and several boys in the stands of the South End Grounds started a fire.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The blaze quickly got out of hand and swept through downtown Boston, destroying or damaging 100 buildings.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Team owners argued with each other, and players hated the NL's $2,400 salary cap.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Many teams also ran into trouble with city governments that forbade recreational activities on Sunday.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Billy Sunday, a prominent outfielder in the 1880s, became so disgusted with the behavior of teammates that he quit playing in 1891 to become one of America's most famous evangelical Christian preachers.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Most fans appear to have felt the same way, because attendance at games was plummeting by 1900.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] After eight seasons as a 12-team league, the NL contracted back to eight teams for the 1900 season, eliminating its teams in Baltimore, Cleveland, Louisville (which has never had another major league team since), and Washington.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] This provided an opportunity for competition.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Three of those cities received franchises in the newly christened American League (AL) when the minor Western League changed its name to the AL in 1900, with the approval of the NL, which regarded the AL as a lesser league since they were a party to the National Agreement.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The AL declined to renew its National Agreement membership when it expired the next year, and on January 28, 1901, the AL officially declared itself a second major league in competition with the NL.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] By 1903, the upstart AL had placed new teams in the National League cities of Boston, Chicago, New York, Philadelphia, and St.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Louis, as well as the "abandoned" NL cities Cleveland and Washington (and, temporarily, Baltimore).
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Only the Cincinnati Reds and Pittsburgh Pirates had no AL team in their markets.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The AL among other things enforced a strict conduct policy among its players.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The National League at first refused to recognize the new league, but reality set in as talent and money was split between the two leagues, diluting the league and decreasing financial success.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] After two years of bitter contention, a new version of the National Agreement was signed in 1903.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] This meant formal acceptance of each league by the other as an equal partner in major-league baseball, mutual respect of player contracts, and an agreement to play a postseason championship—the World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Major League Baseball narrowly averted radical reorganization in November 1920.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Dissatisfied with American League President and National Baseball Commission head Ban Johnson, NL owners dissolved the league on November 8 during heated talks on MLB reorganization in the wake of the Black Sox Scandal.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Four days later, on November 12, both sides met (without Johnson) and agreed to restore the two leagues and replace the ineffective National Commission with a one-man Commissioner in the person of federal Judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The National League circuit remained unchanged from 1900 through 1952.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 1953 the Braves moved from Boston to Milwaukee; in 1966 they moved again, to Atlanta.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 1958 the Brooklyn Dodgers and the New York Giants moved to Los Angeles and San Francisco, respectively, bringing major league baseball to the West Coast of the U.S. for the first time.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The NL remained an eight-team league for over 60 years.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] (For the eight teams, see Expansion (1887–1899) above, and "Classic Eight" below.) In 1962—facing competition from the proposed Continental League and confronted by the American League's unilateral expansion in 1961—the NL expanded by adding the New York Mets and the Houston Colt .45s.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The "Colts" were renamed the Houston Astros three years later.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 1969, the league added the San Diego Padres and the Montreal Expos (now the Washington Nationals), becoming a 12-team league for the first time since 1899.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 1993 the league expanded to 14 teams, adding the Colorado Rockies and the Florida Marlins (which became the Miami Marlins shortly after the end of the 2011 season).
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 1998, the Arizona Diamondbacks became the league's fifteenth franchise, and the Milwaukee Brewers moved from the AL to the NL, giving the NL 16 teams for the next 15 seasons.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 1994, the league was again reorganized, into three geographical divisions (East, West and Central, all currently with five teams; from 1994 to 1997 the West had one fewer team, and from 1998 to 2012, the Central had one more team).
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] A third postseason round was added at the same time: the three division champions plus a wild card team (the team with the best record among those finishing in second place) now advance to the preliminary National League Division Series.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Due to a players' strike, however, the postseason was not actually held in 1994.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Before the 1998 season, the American League and the National League each added a fifteenth team.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Because of the odd number of teams, only seven games could possibly be scheduled in each league on any given day.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Thus, one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] This would have made it difficult for scheduling, in terms of travel days and the need to end the season before October.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In order for MLB officials to continue primarily intraleague play, both leagues would need to carry an even number of teams, so the decision was made to move one club from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Eventually, Milwaukee agreed (after Kansas City declined) to change leagues; the National League now had 16 teams, the American League 14 with the switch.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Beginning with the 2013 season, the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central to the American League West, which now gave both leagues three divisions of five teams each and necessitated interleague play throughout the season.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Often characterized as being a more "traditional" or "pure" league, the National League did not adopt the designated hitter rule until the shortened 2020 season.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Only the American League previously adopted the rule in 1973.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In theory, this meant that the role of the manager was greater in the National League than in the American League, because the NL manager must take offense into account when making pitching substitutions and vice versa.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Overall, there were fewer home runs and runs scored in the National League than in the American, due to the presence of the pitcher in the NL batting order.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] As the collective bargaining agreement came closer to expiring after the 2021 season, owners expressed their intentions to use the designated hitter in all games starting in 2022.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020, rule changes were instituted in both leagues for the 2020 season, which included an abbreviated 60-game schedule, the use of the designated hitter in all games, and expanded rosters.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The National League reverted to its old batting rules during the 2021 season, but starting with the 2022 season, they permanently adopted the designated hitter rule after a new CBA was ratified.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] For the first 96 years of its coexistence with the American League, National League teams faced their AL counterparts only in exhibition games, the All-Star Game, or in the World Series.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Beginning in 1997, however, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Prior to the early 2020s – before the universal designated hitter rule was started in both leagues – as part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the DH rule was used only in games where the American League team was the home team.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 1999, the offices of American League and National League presidents were discontinued and all authority was vested in the Commissioner's office.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The leagues subsequently appointed "honorary" presidents to carry out ceremonial roles such as the awarding of league championship trophies.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Additionally, the distinction between AL and NL umpires was erased, and instead all umpires were unified under MLB control.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Following these actions, as well as the institution of interleague play, little besides the DH rule remained to differentiate the two leagues.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] By 2011, MLB had changed its policy on interleague play, deciding to schedule interleague games throughout the season rather than only during specially designated periods.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] This policy would allow each league to have 15 teams, with one team in each league playing an interleague game on any given day.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] As a condition of the sale of the Astros to Jim Crane in November 2011, the team agreed to move to the American League effective with the 2013 season.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 2023, National League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 American League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 2025, this will be increased to 48 regular season interleague games, 24 at home and 24 on the road.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] As of the end of the 2025 season, the Dodgers have won the most NL pennants, with 26.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Representing the National League against the American League, the Cardinals have won the most World Series (11), followed by the Dodgers (9), Giants (8), Pirates (5), and Reds (5).
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Louis also holds the distinction of being the only AA club to defeat an NL club in the 19th-century version of the World Series, having done so against their now-division rival Cubs.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] , dropped from the National League after the season for refusing to sign a pledge to end beer sales in their park.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The eight-team lineup established in 1900 remained unchanged through 1952.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] All franchises are still in the league, with five remaining in the same city.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The first line is the formation of the National League (NL) in 1876, and the second is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901, signifying the beginning of modern baseball.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The third line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The fourth line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] World Series championships are shown with a "•", National League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "^", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "#".
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] The role of the league president was eliminated.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] In 2001, Bill Giles, son of Warren Giles, was named honorary president of the NL.
[src:freeman-brown/national-league-baseball] Honorary presidents perform only ceremonial duties such as presenting league championship trophies and representing their respective leagues at All-Star Games.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] The **Society for American Baseball Research** (**SABR**) is a membership organization dedicated to fostering the research and dissemination of the history and statistical record of baseball.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] The organization was founded in Cooperstown, New York, on August 10, 1971, at a meeting of 16 "statistorians" coordinated by sportswriter Bob Davids.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] The organization now reports a membership of over 7,500 and is based in Phoenix, Arizona.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] While the acronym "SABR" was used to coin the word sabermetrics (for the use of sophisticated mathematical tools to analyze baseball), the Society is about much more than statistics.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] Well-known figures in the baseball world such as Bob Costas, Keith Olbermann, Craig R.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] Wright, and Rollie Hemond are members, along with highly regarded "sabermetricians" such as Bill James and Rob Neyer.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] Among Major League Baseball players, Jeff Bajenaru was believed to have been (until 2006) the only active player with a SABR membership; Elden Auker, Larry Dierker, and Andy Seminick also have been involved.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] Only a minority of members pursue "number crunching" research.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] SABR members keep in touch through online directories and electronic mailing lists set up through the SABR headquarters.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] The headquarters also maintains a number of research tools on its website, including a lending library, home run and triple play logs, and course syllabi related to the game.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] SABR holds annual conventions in a different city each year.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] The conference generally includes panel discussions, research presentations, city-specific tourism, a ballgame, and an awards banquet.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] The 2017 convention in New York City, set the attendance record with 806 registered attendees out of approximately 7,000 SABR members.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] The organization also hosts an annual baseball analytics conference in Phoenix and a Negro Leagues conference, which is held in a different location each year.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] In 2013, SABR began collaborating with Rawlings on the Gold Glove Award.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] Rawlings changed the voting process to incorporate SABR Defensive Index, a sabermetric component provided by SABR, which accounts for approximately 25 percent of the vote for the defensive award.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] SABR has regional chapters located across the mainland United States.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] There are also a number of international chapters.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] The majority of chapters are named in honor of a player or person with a close connection to, or after something associated with, the chapter's location.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] Chapters are displayed here with their headquartered locations and the wider area they serve, if applicable.
[src:freeman-brown/society-for-american-baseball-research] SABR holds an annual convention in different locations around North America.
